:"1490","1428":"1428","Lewynsmede, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"1409–":"1409–Deceased","1409–Male":"1409–Deceased","1381–1428":"1381–1428","1420–1490":"1420–1490","1378–1430":"1378–1430","1434":"1434","1455":"1455","1378":"1378","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1409":"1409","1381":"1381","1490":"1490","1428":"1428","Lewynsmede, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stephens","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Stevens  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stevens","meanings":["English (London), Flemish, Dutch, and North German: patronymic from the personal name   Steven  . The surname of Flemish origin is also found in the Walloon part of Belgium. In North America, the English form of the surname has also absorbed some like-sounding Jewish names and various other European cognates, e.g. Greek   Stefanidis  , Serbian <b>Stevanović</b> (see   Stevanovic  ), Slovenian and Slovak <b>Štefanič</b> (see   Stefanic  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Forrester","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>forester</i> ‘officer in charge of a forest or lord's hunting ground’ (Old French <i>forestier</i>, Anglo-Norman <i>forester</i>). See   Forrest  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Forister","meanings":["English: variant of   Forrester  ."]},{"name":"Forrest","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: transferred use of the surname, in origin a local name for someone who lived in or by an enclosed wood, Old French <i>forest</i>."]},{"name":"Forester","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Forrester   (see   Forrest  )."]},{"name":"Forrister","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Forrester  ."]},{"name":"Forster","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, an occupational name with at least four possible derivations: from Middle English <i>foster</i> ‘foster parent’, <i>for(e)ster</i> ‘forester’, <i>fors(e)ter</i> ‘shearer’, or <i>fu(y)ster</i> ‘saddle-tree maker’."]}]}],"historicEvents